<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-017-321 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 497 261</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Nov 4 1991 v8 n44 p150(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>HP reorganization paves way for dramatic PC strategy shift.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McCarthy, Vance.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>HP merges its palmtop, desktop, file server, networking andNewWave software business groups into a new division as part of areorganization intended to help HP develop an integrated productstrategy based on client/server computing.andP;  HP is facingincreasing pressure from microcomputer mail order firms and islooking to the new strategy to provide business from customers whoare looking for value-added service.andP;  The move supports HP CEOJohn Young's previous statement that HP would not pursue astand-alone microcomputer strategy.andP;  The new division is headed byRobert Frankenberg, and no layoffs or additional funding isplanned for the change.andP;  Analysts say the reorganization gives HPthe role of systems integrator, which may succeed when coupledwith HP's high-quality technology and hardware.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Hewlett-Packard Co. (Management).andO;Ticker:    HWP.andO;Topic:     ReorganizationClient/Server ArchitectureHand-held computersStrategic PlanningComputer Systems Integration.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>